  whatItMeans: {
    en: "General Obligations Law 7-108 is New York's security deposit statute. A landlord can only deduct for real damage beyond normal wear and tear, plus unpaid rent and similar lawful charges. The same statute caps the deposit at one month's rent and sets a 14-day deadline for return after moveout.\n\nNormal wear and tear. Carpet in a lived-in apartment fades, flattens, and shows traffic paths. That is normal. Tenants are not responsible for those effects. Gradual fading, matted traffic paths, minor spots from ordinary living, and general aging all count as wear and tear.\n\nDamage. Large stains that will not clean, cigarette burns, pet urine damage, rips, holes, and areas shredded by pets are damage. Those can be chargeable. The amount, though, depends on the age of the carpet.\n\nUseful life. Apartment-grade carpet has a useful life of about 5 to 10 years in industry practice. Courts and housing counselors use that range to decide what a landlord can charge. Carpet past its useful life has essentially no remaining value. A landlord cannot charge the full cost of new carpet when the old carpet was already due for replacement.\n\nThe math. If a carpet was 6 years old when the tenant moved in, and the tenant lived there 2 years, the carpet is 8 years old at moveout. If the useful life is 10 years, 2 years of useful life remain out of 10 — that is 20% of replacement cost at most, only if the tenant damaged the carpet. On a $2,000 replacement, that is $400 — not $2,000. If the carpet was already past its useful life (10+ years on a 10-year carpet), the chargeable amount is typically zero, even for damage, because the carpet had no remaining value.\n\nAge documentation. The landlord often knows when the carpet was installed — receipts, prior leases, or maintenance records show the date. A tenant can request the age of the carpet in writing. When the landlord cannot show a recent install date, the tenant's assumption of age at move-in (supported by move-in photos) usually wins.\n\nThe 14-day itemized statement. GOL 7-108 requires the landlord to return the deposit, or an itemized statement of every deduction, within 14 days of moveout. A landlord who misses the 14-day deadline can forfeit the right to deduct anything — the tenant is entitled to the full deposit back.\n\nEvidence that wins cases. Dated move-in photos (especially time-stamped phone photos) of every room, with close-ups of existing stains, matted traffic paths, and worn edges. Dated moveout photos in the same angles. The written lease and any move-in checklist the landlord provided. A receipt for a professional carpet cleaning before moveout — the cleaning cost (often $100 to $200) is usually far less than a disputed replacement charge.\n\nSmall claims. A tenant with a disputed carpet deduction can file in small claims court (up to $5,000 in town or village court, $10,000 in city court). No attorney is required. The itemized statement, the photos, the lease, and proof of carpet age are the core evidence.\n\nRent-regulated units. In a rent-stabilized or rent-controlled apartment, additional DHCR rules apply. Overcharges tied to 'renovation' of worn-out carpet can raise separate Major Capital Improvement questions; that piece belongs with DHCR."
  },

